data.description: Hi everyone! The next Q&A session will be tomorrow. See you then!

data.message: Take a few deep breaths to center yourself the next time your cravings are getting to you. Try it out today and tell us how it went. Were you able to put off lighting up for a little while? #feeling healthy
For about an hour. Works just so stressful this week it's hard to control my cravings

Big Tobacco is advertising E-Cigarettes as a safer and better way to smoke, but studies have shown that they still contain toxins. Why do you think so many people are ready to adopt them even before proper research has been conducted? #e-cig
Fads. People think it's better because we make it and not grow it. They think why would they make a harmful substance in a lab to be inhaled

Breathing and relaxation techniques can really help when you quit and enrich your daily life. Here’s a link describing a few different techniques: http://quitsmoking.about.com/od/cravingsandurges/a/deepbreaths.htm. Try one out and tell us how it went. Which one works best for you? #feeling healthy
I usually take deep breaths as that's been drilled into me from therapy for anxiety etc.

It’s no shock that Tobacco companies spend loads of time and money thinking of how to appeal to a younger crowd with fresh lungs. Check out this document straight from a major Tobacco Company. How does it feel to be targeted by a huge, expensive marketing campaign? #being conscious

Flavored cigarettes have been outlawed for years now, yet e-cig companies are using old tricks to gain new customers while they still can. Would you have started smoking when you were younger if the product you used was flavored like your favorite candy? #ecig
Probably. I smoked spice before because it was flavored

Part of the new Tobacco Legislation is that physicians and clinicians must encourage and help their smoking patients to quit smoking. Do you think help from a health professional would motivate you to quit? #smoking affects all
No it just irritates me when my doc says anything. That's not why I made the apt
Hi guys, I am available for the next hour. Let me know if you have any questions!
None tonight, thanks
You are welcome, 10009!
Gotta run, but before I leave I wanted to give you some ideas how to cope when withdrawal hits. Happy Thanksgiving everyone!
Who’s that one friend you can count on to listen to you about what’s going on? Who will you be able to trust as your supporter when you are ready to quit smoking? #support
My dad.

Now that you’ve made your list of Cons for quitting smoking, let’s consider your top reason NOT to quit. Post your #1 Con for quitting here and tell us why it’s your biggest concern. Finish this sentence: "I want to quit smoking, but I'm worried that ________."Feel free to discuss with other group members concerns about quitting. #being conscious
I want to quit smoking but I'm worried that I will feel suffocated not going outside during the day. Seems stupid though. That's not a good reason not to quit lol
All change has pros and cons. What are some of the cons of quitting smoking? Why would it be hard?  #being conscious
A major con for me would be that I wouldn't go outside much. I'm pretty much only outside of I'm smoking.

Quitting smoke can help preserve our planet! Without cigarette smoke, the chances of household fires decrease and less secondhand smoke is added into the air we breathe. Can you think of any other environmental improvements that might result from less smoke? Share them here:  #being conscious
Less forest fires and wild fires from people throwing butts out the window

What strategy do you plan to use when you do decide to quit smoking? Will you use nicotine replacement therapy (like patch or gum? Medication? Cold turkey? Counseling? Post&Share your plan of action here and see if any other group members are on your same page.: #being conscious
Cold turkey. Vegetables when I'm craving

data.message: Hello everyone! I hope all is well. This group has been a bit quiet so I just wanted to remind you all that you will receive $1 for each day that you comment on a daily post. You can earn up to $90! I also wanted to reiterate that this group is for you all in your contemplation about quitting. As questions or concerns come up, you can always reach us here at TSP and we will respond as fast as we can. It is also encouraged that you interact with the other members of your group to make this experience better. One last thing, the Dr. Is In sessions are there so you can have a first hand chat with someone who is qualified to help you on your journey. If you aren't able to comment on the daily posts, you can speak to the doctor about the posts or about any questions that you might have. Looking forward to hearing from more of you soon.Best,D'Arius from TSP
It has been pretty quiet here ha
On a scale of 1-10, how important is it to you to quit smoking for good? #being conscious
Eight. I need to but it's not my top priority yet
Do you know anyone who has died from a tobacco related disease? How did their death affect your own smoking? Post&Share your experiences #reflection
My mom's mom died but it didn't change anything for me. People die it happens.
Hi guys, let me know if you have any questions! I will be online for the next hour.
I'm more addicted to the action of smoking. Actually bringing the thing to my mouth. Any suggestions so I don't end up eating a lot?

Great question 10009! This is a sort of question I get quite often in the TSP groups. Some suggestions would be to find a low calorie snack, some people really like celery, for example. Sugar free gum is another great alternative. If you are interested in nicotine replacement therapy, you could also use a nicotine gum. Any of these sound like they could be an option for you?
Looks like I'll be buying celery :)
Great! If you get tired of all the celery, other vegetable sticks like carrots, cucumbers, green pepper etc. are good options, too.
That's actually really helpful, thanks! Any tips for clearing out the lungs? I cough up black bits now

You know, if you quit smoking, it is actually pretty normal that the lung will try to get rid of all toxins initially - this should get better within a couple of weeks. Starting a modest sports regimen can help you rebuilding your lung capacity (walking/jogging, swimming, joga is great, too because of the focus on breathing). Drinking lots of water or herbal tea will help you to flush the toxins from your body (even though that may not directly clean your lungs).

Ok guys, I've got to run. Feel free to leave additional comments if anything comes up during the week. Since some of the posts last week were about e-cigarettes, I wanted to give you some additional information before I take off: The problem with e-cigs is that there is no clear data up to now showing that they really help smokers quit. Also, they are not regulated by the FDA, which means that it is unclear what is in them. For all we know, they may still be harmful to your health. I would recommend using nicotine replacement therapy: gum, patch, inhaler (prescription), or lozenge (prescription). Also, other prescription medication like zyban or chantix can be effective, but you have to talk to your doctor first to get a prescription. I recommend trying one of these options before trying an e-cig.Check this for additional information http://smokefree.gov/e-cigarettes.

Did you know that the number of nonsmokers that are affected by second hand smoke more than doubles the number of actual smokers in the U.S.? Who is affected by your second hand smoke?. #smoking affects all
My dad mostly. I smoke in my car and we carpool to work.
Hi everyone, I will be online for an hour now to answer any questions you guys have around smoking, quitting, or the TSP study.
You guys were pretty quiet today. Let me know if anything comes up during the next week. I will be back for the next session a week from now.
No one participates in this group and the time slot is during work hours for me.

Hi 10009, this week I will hold the session at a different time (Thursday 2-3 pm Pacific). If you have any question and are not able to make it during that time you can always leave me a comment here and I can answer it then.

data.message: Everyone wants to know whether electronic cigarettes can help smokers quit. Unfortunately studies are showing that they are not any more effective than a placebo. So health professionals still recommend using well-studied strategies like counseling or nicotine replacement therapy (patch, gum) when you’re ready to quit. Which strategies are you thinking about using? #e-cig
Wellbutrin or cold turkey. I figure when I'm ready I'll quit. Did it before gonna do it again

Remember Drawback #1 ("I don't want to have withdrawal symptoms") from yesterday’s post? Which one of our following comebacks would work for you? #balance • I can tell myself that some withdrawal symptoms are actually signs that my body is healing• I can tell myself that I may be coughing more because the cilia (hair-like structures that line my lungs and clean the air I breathe) that were paralyzed by the cigarette smoke are starting to work again, which makes me temporarily cough more• I can tell myself I may have tingling in my arms and legs because my circulation is improving
The first one. Having kicked other addictions in my life that helped me. Just knowing my body is healing.

Research shows making the benefits of quitting more important than the drawbacks helps smokers quit their habit for good. So try your hand at making a negative a positive and tell us, what's your comeback for this drawback? #balance
There is aids to quit smoking such as Chantix and nicotine supplements and if you can afford to quit, you can afford the supplements to quit
Get a prescription for wellbutrin. I quit for six months with that. Cigarettes just tasted disgusting after I was on that.

Here are some things to help you maintain your physique when you stop smoking. Read them over and tell us what sounds like it would help you the most. #balance • Make sure you have a well-balanced diet• Chew sugarless gum when you want something sweet• Eat slowly• Plan healthy, low-fat and low-calorie snacks into your day• Watch portion sizes• Read food labels
I think one of the biggest things here is proportion sizes. I quit for three months at one point and didn't gain any weight when I watched proportion and ate a protein with every meal
Watch portion sizes for me. I over eat when I don't pay attention.

Avoiding weight gain is on the top of the list of concerns for almost every smoker. We get it and have made a list of some tips that can help keep your weight on track while you quit. Pick which one sounds best to you. How could you implement it into your life? #balance• Go for a walk, swim, bike ride or any exercise you enjoy• Find small ways to be more active like taking the stairs instead of the elevator or parking a little further away• Find alternatives to snacking like calling a friend• Drink some extra water
Drink more water. Hangout with people. Avoid situations that are triggers
Many e-cig companies are actually owned by BIG TOBACCO companies. What do you think their motives are? Remain a loyal customer? Help you quit smoking? Other ideas?
Money. That's all they care about anyway. Trying to monopolize the industry.
What would be the best-case scenario if you quit smoking? #balance

That picture was mirrored. Interesting. Best case if I quit smoking I'd be able to breathe better. It doesn't really cost me much because I roll my own. I feel like I'm the only one participating in this "group". Btw. Still waiting for the first gift card. If others are still waiting I don't blame them for not participating.

For any of you that aren’t sure what an e-cig is, take a look at this FDA page explaining what they are and some of the controversy surrounding their regulations. Do any of you feel that if you were a minor, an e-cig would be more appealing and seem “safer” to try than a traditional cigarette? #being conscious

I would totally believe they are safer. If I were a kid again I could see these leading to a higher usage rate as the risk of getting caught by parents etc is so much lower compared to conventional cigarettes

The time has come everyone! Tomorrow we will be starting our posts. Remember that you get paid for every post that you comment on so please try and respond to all or as many posts as you can. You can also speak to the other group members and make it interactive. We will also be having our weekly " the Dr. Is In" sessions with a clinical psychologist so be on the look out for that. Really looking forward to hearing from all of you soon!-D'Arius from TSP
How would you support someone who tells you they want to quit smoking? #motivation
I simply don't smoke in their presence. In addition I don't let them bum from me. I'll also refrain from smoking in my car and I use a scent if I'm going to be around them.
Educate yourself on the smoking rates and laws in your state. Check out the “Smoking Information” and “Smoking bans” in your state. Did any of the information surprise you? #smoking affects all
I still think smoking bans at bars have to be bad for business it kinda makes smokers not want to go. Restaurants too

When I was in college they tried banning smoking within the campus but the students voted against it. I read that the local colleges are all smoke free now. I don't think I would have been able to do that when I was in school. It took thirty minutes to get back to my car. Can't imagine taking forty minutes out of my day for one smoke.
Hello everyone! We will be having the first "Dr Is In" session this coming Wednesday, November 12th, from 5-6 pm Pacific Time.
Share a success that you have had in the past. It can be anything from any time. Why did it work? Who helped? #motivation

The most recent big success I can think of is landing my last job. It was obviously a success, I love what I do, who I work with and I'm great at my job. Pay isn't bad either. My father was a large part in this, providing the transportation I needed until I could afford a car for the 75 mile round trip daily.

The time has come everyone! Today we will be starting our posts. Remember that you get paid for every post that you comment on so please try and respond to all or as many posts as you can. At the end of the study you all will receive your money. We encourage you all to speak to the other group members and make this experience as interactive and helpful as possible. We will also be having our weekly " The Dr. Is In" sessions with a clinical psychologist so be on the look out for that. Really looking forward to hearing from all of you! -D'Arius from TSP

What are the Dr is in sessions? Speaking of money, do we get a lump at the end including the money for the initial survey? The way the email was worded it sounded like it would be sent to us sooner..?

Hi 10009, the Dr is in sessions are going to be a time for you all to speak with the clinical psychologist. He will answer questions that you have about quitting smoking, provide support and group counseling, and provide resources for you in your journey to quitting. Regarding the money from the initial survey, you should have already received that, so we can look into that for you if you have not yet received it.
When will the doctor be in? And could you also look in to my gift card please?

I don't believe I ever got it unless it went to my spam and deleted. Not sure if replying to the email was where I went wrong instead of creating a new one. I had no idea there was going to be sessions like that, pretty cool guys

Happy Halloween and welcome to the study! Just wanted to let everyone know that we are still in the process of adding more people so please be patience with us as we will start soon. Thank you for your participation and we are so excited to get started! -D'Arius from TSP

data.message: Not sure if I'll be on so I'll ask my question here, what do you know about nrt lozenges effectiveness? I resort to smoking a cigarette at work to get rid of my headache so I can actually work but I'm wondering if this would help that..

Hi 10009, first off it's great that your are trying to quit/reduce your smoking. Keep up the good work! The lozenge is definitely at least as effective for smoking cessation as other nicotine replacement products and I think it could be a good option for helping with your withdrawal symptoms. You can get it over the counter at a pharmacy and it even comes in different flavors like mint or cherry. Do you think you will give it a try?
